ary filmmakers, including George Burdeau and Victor Masayesva, Jr. He shows how Native filmmaking incorporates traditional concepts such as the connection to place, to the sacred, and to the cycles of nature. While these concepts now find expression through Westernized media, they also maintain continuity with earlier aesthetic productions. In this way, Native filmmaking serves to create and preserve a sense of identity for indigenous people.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aAesthetics. 0aDocumentary filmsxHistory and criticism. 0aIndian aesthetics. 0aIndian art. 0aIndiansxEthnic identity. 0aVisual anthropology. 7aART / History / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/74702940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292758797423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292758797/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK